article.description: Lydia Bauer scored a career-high 27 points and Wisconsin-Green Bay easily beat Wright State 95-65 in the Horizon League tournament semifinals.
article.headline: Green Bay dumps Wright State to reach Horizon final
article.linkText: Bauer's career-high 27 points power Green Bay
article.story:
GREEN BAY, Wis. --  There would be no surprise early exit this year from the Horizon League tournament for Wisconsin-Green Bay.

The top-seeded Phoenix (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP), who lost in the Horizon semifinals at home last season, didn't let history repeat itself and advanced to Sunday afternoon's championship game with a 95-65 win over Wright State on Friday night.

"It was neat to see in walkthrough today there wasn't the tension. I think last year in the semifinal game there was a lot of tension in that game. The kids just had trouble relaxing," said Green Bay coach Matt Bollant. "I think we're just a little older, a little more mature and I think we have a little more confidence that good things are going to happen."

Good things have happened all season for the Phoenix (31-1), who won their 22nd straight game and have pounded their first two tournament foes by a combined 77 points.

Sophomore reserve Lydia Bauer hit six 3-pointers and scored a career-high 27 points Friday as Green Bay put up a Kress Center single-game points record.

"Lydia's growing up right before our eyes and it's really fun to watch," said Phoenix senior guard Celeste Hoewisch. "I think we've got a star on our hands and it was really amazing to watch. She's developed into such a nightmare to guard."

Kayla Tetschlag added 18 points, five rebounds and five assists, Hoewsich added 17 points and Julie Wojta had her sixth double-double in 10 games with 16 points and 12 rebounds.

The Phoenix will host No. 2 seed Butler -- which Green Bay beat 93-57 at home just two weeks ago -- with an automatic berth to the NCAA tournament on the line. And even though Green Bay is a lock to get an at-large berth no matter the outcome, Bollant said nothing is being taken for granted.

"I think they're humble enough to know anything can happen and that's what we said in the locker room, 'Remember how hard you played at senior day. You didn't just show up to beat Butler the way you did. You played your butt off and you played hard and you played well,'" Bollant said. "Let's make sure that's our focus again because certainly Butler with three good seniors, they believe this is their chance."

LaShawna Thomas kept Wright State (19-12) relatively close with 13 of her 21 points in the first half. Shauna Sandifer and Ta-myra Davis each added 13 points for the Raiders.
